To all,<br><br>
I have often wondered why, after thirty years for me, (almost to the day that I returned) that Vietnam still exists so often in my mind.<br><br>
One of my answers is that my (our) experiences in Vietnam are &quot;little&quot; different from what happens in the rest of life.<br><br>
I am sure that Ed, who I assume from what he was written about PTSD, is quite knowlegable about the subject.  The rest of you are as well.  I have a personal affinity to Gary, for a reason I'm not sure why.  Maybe it's the grunt in us.  Or to be perfectly frank -- it's the frankness of &quot;shared experiences.&quot;<br><br>
More to the point.  I have often thought of what &quot;healing&quot; means.  I don't want to (will not&quot; let my experiences of Vietnam go.  I did it for too many years.  There are many &quot;lessons&quot; to learn from the Vietnam &quot;experience.<br><br>
Does healing mean that the memories of the war don't traumaticlly (sp) affect future choices and daily decisions in our lives?  I know that my biggest frustaration and cause of depression comes from the &quot;fact&quot; that lessons I learned in life don't affect the world as fast or as well as I would like it to.  I won't be offended if anyone calls me an egoist for that last statement.  <br><br>
Ed recently wrote that he didn't care how the war got started.  He was more concerned with the aftereffects on the troops.  (paraphrased)  I share his compassion.  I also enjoy his humor.  I have lauged out loud at his outrageousness.  I will,  hopefully confront him one time if I ever get to visit my brother who lives in Oklahoma.<br><br>
Cook, I have done my best to never make Marine jokes.  Your gift to me of the jacket keeps me to my promise -- tough I amy some day break it.  You are a man different from me, who I admire -- to a large extent.  You have gone from extreme to the other -- retaliton to concillation.  I' m impressed.<br><br>
But back to healing.  What do you all want from this site?  I know that I want opinions different from my own.  I, should mention that I want them with class -- for whatever that means.  I don't care what others say; I just want to be treated with respect.  I earned it.<br><br>
I like the &quot;welcome greetings&quot; that I have receieved over the years.  I am more proud of my actions in Vietnam than if the fact that I did it in the place of another man.<br><br>
Being twenty years old is hard enough.  We can't relive our pasts but it is our conversations here that can close some of the gaps.  More late.<br><br>
Paul
